\begin_layout Section
Flexibility
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider 2 different positive NPV projects, with the same cost of capital.
 Assume project B is more expensive, longer and is more volatile - thus
 project A is better.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now, assume these 2 projects are technologies (require R&D) and that they
 are 
\series bold
not
\series default
 mutually exclusive.
 If 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

taking both technologies
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is better than taking only one of them, which one of them should be taken
 first? Most economists choose A, yet it is the wrong answer - as the NPV
 of taking B first is bigger than if taking A first.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Flexibility is 
\series bold
not
\series default
 just about 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

radnomness
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 - but about the ability to choose one project before the other one.
 It might lead to counter-intuitive results sometimes.
 The cost of doing any projects comes from 2 sources: the 
\series bold
direct
\series default
 cost, and the 
\series bold
indirect
\series default
 cost (the cost of replacing already existing technology - 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

optimal search policy
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, Weizman's 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Pandora's Box
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 problem).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The intuition for choosing B first is that in the good case it provides
 extreme value, while in the bad case it can be corrected with A.
 The rarest, most volatile (even with a lower NPV) project must be first,
 for the probability of a good outcome.
\end_layout

